And in the same vein, a majority of American governments enacted new laws that made registration or voting difficult from 2009.
This phenomenon has expanded following the November 2010 elections, which saw the increase of 675 new Republican representatives in 26 states.
Accordingly, 180 bills were introduced during 2011 restricting the exercise of the right to vote in 41 states.
The new electoral laws require voters to present an identity document with a photograph, in addition to a proof of American citizenship.
On the other hand, these laws reduce the periods of advance voting, invalidate the right to register as an elector on polling day and withdraw their right to vote for citizens with criminal record.
Before the 2006 elections, no American state required voters to submit an identity document with photography.
The State of Indiana was the first to demand it.
The United States Supreme Court confirmed in 2008 the constitutionality of the Indian law.
Therefore, the Republican authorities rushed to extend this practice to other states.
In recent years these authorities have supported bills in 34 states to force voters to submit an identity document with photography.
It is important to bear in mind that, unlike what happens in Quebec, American citizens do not have a universal identity document, such as the Social Security Card.
In fact, 11 per cent of American citizens, i.e. 21 million people of voting age, do not have any photo identity documents issued by a government agency in their state.
On the other hand, five million new voters in 2012 lack an identity document with these characteristics.
But, often, obtaining the required identity document costs more than $100.
Thus, new restrictions disproportionately affect young people, minorities and people with low incomes.
Indeed, 25 per cent of African Americans, 15 per cent of people earn less than $35,000 a year, 18 per cent of citizens over 65 and 20 per cent of voters between the ages of 18 and 29 do not have an identity document with photography.
