With the bitcoin, all network nodes are both depositaries of accounting books, verifiers, currency issuers and buyers and sellers.
How does that network work?
Each transaction between two users is actually made between two e-mail addresses.
A user can choose a different address for each payment, thus guaranteeing anonymity.
A set of information related to this transaction is signed electronically through a double-key encryption system.
The network can thus verify the authenticity of the transaction.
Thanks to the content of the file, it is also possible to ensure that the changes of bitcoins consist of the public account book, which is spread throughout the network.
The key milestone is to write that new transaction into that book.
This goes through the resolution of a mathematical challenge launched to computers and the winner, a sort of provisional central banker, will have the privilege to add that complementary line.
It is a phase of file-cutting, i.e. transforming a large file into a shorter and more unique numerical footprint.
The computers "cogene" the new transaction and add a number before "trace" the set.
The goal is to find the number that offers a particular footprint (more zero at the beginning).
Once that number is found, the other nodes easily verify that it is the good one.
The transaction is then indestructibly linked to the chain of sets of other transactions; any modification would change the fingerprint.
If, to commit a fraud, one user would like to pay twice with the same money very quickly (in less than ten minutes), the network would accept only one of the two transactions as valid; the other would be orphaned, as both have different fingerprints.
The computer that solves the challenge takes 50 bitcoins.
To avoid inflation, this reward is divided into two regularly, probably by the end of 2012.
The number of bitcoins in circulation is therefore limited to 21 million, but they are divisible up to the 100 millionth, leaving a wide margin.
The difficulty of this challenge is also revealed in each increase in the calculus power.
The life of the network already has its heights.
The websites that offer Bitcoin services have been attacked and bitcoins stolen in storage.
