A Constitution with Forces in Egypt
It's a new double or nothing from President Mohammed Morsi.
While Egypt is more divided than ever as regards the constitutional declaration, which temporarily grants it full powers, he decided to play the whole.
He took everyone by surprise on Wednesday, when he announced that the Constituent Assembly would vote on its final text the following day.
Just a week ago, the Head of State had given that Assembly two more months to finish its work.
And nearly two years ago, Egypt used a provisional text, several times modified, which weakened institutional stability and led to judicial fraud.
This new initiative has only increased the fracture in the country.
For his opponents, the president perseveres in his "autocratic delirium" and continues to "tray his word" and "trail the law."
On the part of its supporters, it is ensured that this is a measure to speed up the institutional and political crisis and accelerate the transition process.
A referendum should be held in the next 15 days.
A very short period of time requiring the Brothers to renounce their draft to explain the text, article by article, to the Egyptians.
For the president, it is also a way of recovering a popular and democratic legitimacy while the controversy causes damage throughout the country.
Mohammed Morsi seems convinced that the Egyptians will vote for him, as he said in an interview to the American weekly Time.
Considering that this appeal has been voted very quickly, it contains an ultimatum for the Egyptian people: "or they vote on my text or I maintain full powers", powers which are supposed to end with the adoption of the Constitution.
It is in this strange environment in which 85 members of this Constituent Assembly, Islamist largely, voted the text yesterday.
Most liberals did not go to the summons.
In mid-November, just before the constitutional declaration, they had closed the door because they felt they could not enforce their views.
The representatives of human rights, religious minorities and civil society did the same.
In order to achieve the necessary quorum yesterday morning, 11 people, substitute members, were added in a hurry.
Some of them are very close to the Muslim Brothers.
As I had hoped, the articles voted were unanimously.
On the other hand, the commentators are pleased that one of the few discrepancies in the day has been expressed practically at the time of prayer, so much so that several members of the committee came to think that the Constituent's watch was wrong.
The text, which was still being voted on yesterday, consists of 234 articles.
Article 2, subject to all looks, remains at last identical to that of the 1971 Constitution, which stipulated that “the principles of Sharia constitute the main source of law”.
Salafist parties, for whom the establishment of Islamic law is a fundamental claim, hoped that "the principles" could be replaced by "the rules", which would have allowed stricter application.
For Islamists, this article has not been modified is a guarantee of their goodwill and respect for the other components of Egyptian society.
Liberals view it as hypocritical and consider it nothing more than an advertising craft.
According to them, the Islamization of the Constitution is done through other articles.
They refer, in particular, to article 220, which confers an advisory role on Al-Azhar University, in particular for anyone who has to confirm its conformity with the laws of Sharia.
According to Egypt specialist Sophie Pommier, it is disturbing because "people called to pronounce are not elected and have no democratic legitimacy.
Here we see the premises of a theocracy."
The fears of the liberals are further increased by the fact that the next rector of that university would be much less moderate than the present one.
"For now, there is no concrete religious implication.
With this Constitution we are within the framework of the civil status.
Most jurists who have worked in this text are not Ulemas but university students, some of them formed in the French system," Alexis Blouet explains, who prepares a thesis on the Egyptian constitutional transition.
But he recognizes that there may be some ambiguity around article 220, since the terms used imitate the religious vocabulary.
"We refer specifically to the term iqh [Islamic jurisprudence, ndlr].
And the question that might arise in the future would be to what extent are the civil judges competent to pronounce themselves above all of this."
Beyond its religious character, the text voted yesterday has received many criticisms concerning the extended powers conferred on the President of the Republic.
The Muslim Brothers will claim that they are few compared to those during the previous regime.
Another conflicting point: the powers conferred on the army.
In accordance with the wishes of the military, the revision of the defence budget will not be submitted to Parliament, but to a national defence council.
Nor would civil prosecutions in military courts be prohibited, as requested by human rights associations.
They also expressed their concerns about the text, which they consider to be liberticide.
The crime of blasphemy is maintained and, from now on, insults are prohibited, which could lead to serious consequences for freedom of expression, especially that of the press.
In addition, no article emphasizes the protection of women, stresses Heba Morayef of Human Rights Watch.
According to her, the only positive has been the prohibition of torture in accordance with article 36.
The word was not contained in the previous Constitution.
Although the Egyptian president had to go out last night on television, demonstrations are scheduled for noon.
The supporters of the Head of State protested on Saturday.
