It must be said that even those countries that we take as a model must face a large number of problems.
If it weren't, they wouldn't have benefited from collaborating with our office, wouldn't it?
As regards the legislation of our country, what did the amendment of the law on public procurement mean for your Office? Is it in any way apparent its impact?
Given that the period of validity of this amendment is relatively short, it has not yet been manifested in the control proceedings.
Since we carry out ex post checks, we need to have a certain delay.
For now, it is seen in the process of preparing future controls: we have initiated a new tool for "non-economic risk detection", whereby we have released almost 14,000 public awards, which have been analysed. The changes will be perfectly reflected here, as the limits are modified, the conditions of some types of the selection process are rectified and similar.
Do you consider the adoption of this law to be beneficial or rather a blunder for the bureaucratic system?
I think this law is certainly a step in the right direction and I hope so.
The problem that may arise is that the regulations "harden" and that it is impossible to comply with it.
Already with the previous legislation, controlled persons were linked to the contractor (e.g. in the case of regional operational programmes of the regional council), and every law not respected in the matter of public procurement meant a violation of budgetary discipline.
Does it then make sense to harden the law this way?
I don't think so.
The system should exclude those who want to attack or take advantage of it and not punish those who make a formal decision, which has no impact on decision-making.
Such a system will only create greater bureaucratic pressure.
And how do you get out of this?
We'll see where this path leads us.
The Prime Minister recently stated that the SDG would not bother entrepreneurs with controls of the so-called švarc system, with reference to being autonomous only on paper. What does this mean?
Is the švarc system forbidden or allowed?
The law must be regulated in some way and, if it prohibits anything, then even the Prime Minister of the Government cannot prevent the performance of the Office that has an obligation to carry out such checks and require obligations.
You can say, "We change the law and allow it," but you can't say that we'll do as if nothing.
In the Public Procurement Act, the regulation is quite strict as to how formal action should be taken, and that is how it should be to protect public competition.
But, on the other hand, it is tragic that the candidate should be excluded with the best offer not to meet the formal requirements.
The law will never be perfect, but its application must be correct. This, in my opinion, is what we lack.
