Poland and the cosmos.
At the meeting of Ministers of the European Space Agency countries held last week, Poland was accepted as a twelfth member of ESA. It is the second member country of ESA of the former bloc of Eastern Europe, after the Czech Republic, which became a full member on 12 November 2008.
Poland began intense collaboration with ESA in 1994 and during subsequent years participated in the Agency's project commission.
However, Poland's path to the cosmos began a long time ago.
Polish enthusiasts were already engaged in space flights before World War II, although their work was not always understood.
I remember, for example, the conference of A. Šternfeld at the Warsaw astronomical observatory in which, on 6 December 1933, he presented his ideas on the pioneer study "Introduction to Cosmonautica".
The ideas of the young engineer (born 1905) left the assistants indifferent and, years later, Šternfeld recalled that Dr. Jan Gadomski had been the only one who had shown interest in his work.
In 1934 Šternfeld won in France the Robert Esnault-Pelterie award and André Louis Hirsch for his "Introduction to Cosmonautics".
Dr. Jan Gadomski (1899 - 1966), mentioned earlier, later became a great promoter of astronomy and cosmonautics.
He published hundreds of articles in Polish magazines and wrote a series of books dedicated to this scientific discipline.
Gadomski became a promoter of cosmonautics, he was known all over the world and his contribution to science was rewarded when his name was named one of the craters on the hidden face of the moon.
As early as 1925, a drain was built in Poland and was to be supplied with a rocket engine.
Unfortunately, it is not known who was the author of the proposal and neither are the details of the project known.
It is not clear whether the rocket was going to be used for the start of the dresin or for its braking.
Information on this drain is limited to the collection in the press of the time.
From 1933 the Polish artillery began to dedicate itself to missiles.
The research was funded by Komórka Techniki Uzbrojenia in collaboration with Prof. Mieczyslawem Wolfkem and Prof. Gustavem Mokrzyckiegim.
From the preserved material, it is evident that the investigation came to the stage of practical testing.
However, with the arrival of the German troops, the investigation was discontinued.
In 1937 the prototype of a photoelectric hunting missile designed by engineer Rohoziński appeared in the specialized press and the following year the study "Rakieta - torpeda powiettrzna and rakietomba lotnicza" by author Leliwa-Krzywoblocki was published.
Both projects were intended for military use of missile engines.
Shortly before the war, the Interim Scientific Advisory Committee (Tymczasowy Doradczo-Naukowy) was responsible for all draft missile techniques for military use and coordinated all work.
The committee was founded in 1937, but after two years of activity, it was interrupted by the beginning of the war.
Other studies dedicated to cosmonautics appeared in the Polish press after the war thanks to the work of the Polish Society of Astronautica (Polskie Towarzystwo Astronautyczne).
In the November 1954 issue of Problemy magazine, reference is made for the first time to society with four very extensive articles dedicated to astronomy.
In one of them, Professor M. Subotowicze proposed the creation of a society that would be dedicated to cosmonautics.
At that time artificial satellite projects had already been launched and it was obvious that cosmic research was a discipline with prospects for the future.
Since early 1956 the Polish Society of Astronautics (PTA) had aspired to be part of the International Federation of Astronautics (founded in 1951) and in the fall of that same year the PTA became a full member.
The following year the first president of the PTA, Kazimierz Zarankiewicz (1902 - 1959), became the vice president of the International Federation of Astronautics.
He served this post until his death in 1959.
Starting in 1956, the PTA participated significantly in the development of the RM (Rakieta Meteorologiczna) probe, which was a success and became the first Polish rocket in which scientific research was carried out.
The first type RM-1 was completed in 1957 and launched for the first time on 10 October 1958.
The rocket had a height of 1,800 meters, about 80 cm in length and did not reach 5 kg in weight.
Later, the RM-1A version was completed, and in the summer of 1959 the two-stage RM-2 rockets air trials were started in the Błędów desert.
The rocket was 1.4 meters long and weighed about 11.5 kg.
Another type of developing rocket was going to be the subject of real scientific study. The RM-34 rocket was going to have a peak of 14.5 km and its mission would be to control the high wind.
However, in 1962 the work was suspended.
The successor of the first RM rockets was the Meteor-1 rocket, which was built during 1962 and 1965.
It was designed as a two-step rocket with a total length of 510 cm and an initial weight of 32.5 kg.
Three types (called Meteor-1A, -1B and -1C) were developed, which differed from each other by the space available for scientific devices.
In the Meteor-1A rocket the available space for the volume was 0.4 litres, in the Meteor-1B of 0.34 litres and in the Meteor-1C of 0.62 litres.
The maximum peak in the three types was 37 km.
Between 1965 and 1968, the Meteor-2 rocket was developed at the Air Institute, whose first air tests began in October 1970.
The Meteor-2 rocket had an initial weight of 380 kg and was able to carry a useful weight of 10 kg up to 60 km in height.
Subsequently, the Meteor-2H and Meteor-3 version was built.
It is also necessary to mention Poland's entry into the COSPAR (Committee for Space Research) in 1960 and the formation of the national committee of COSPAR two years later.
Within the framework of the Interkosmos programme, Poland joined the research of the cosmic space on Soviet artificial satellites and, in 1978, the Polish pilot Miroslaw Hermaszewski became the second intercosmonaut after Vladimir Remek.
