Details about the operation remained secret for a long time, the film has been made from Tony Mendez's memories.
Affleck's film is a unique combination of various genres.
On the one hand, a realistic political thriller; on the other, a so-called "caper movie", the story of an episode that went well, a deception (an example can be the Ocean's Eleven series).
The film combines the mood states. We found well-documented sequences of Tehran on the one hand. In the sequence of credits, emblematic photographs of the time of events are shown, which were equally portrayed in the film; there are not many differences in this respect.
On the other hand, typical scenes of Hollywood a little lighter, marked by irony and a slight exaggeration.
And also, scenes from the CIA central and other institutions: men brought along who analyze the situation at the negotiating table, in the corridors of the office, by telephone...
Ben Affleck has managed to restart his career in an excellent way.
The actor, who had been ridiculed, has become a respectable director and his way of acting has ceased to be the target of ironic remarks.
Argo is his third feature film, after "Goodbye Small, Goodbye" (2007) and the thriller "The Town. City of Thieves" (2010).
At the same time, it is Affleck's first film in which action does not take place in the city of Boston, where it grew up.
Also, the sensitivity to capture the atmosphere of the place was a characteristic that placed old movie directors above Hollywood standards.
And Affleck shows it in Argo, where Tehran is "wheeled" in Canada.
The best scenes of the film take place on the streets, in the reconstruction of the true events. The introductory sequence of the embassy's take is impressive due to its synoptic capacity which, at the same time, conveys the emotion of uncertainty and the lack of foresight that arises when, somewhere, history takes a step forward.
Affleck and his collaborators get a similar effect on the fictional scenes (the imposter team in the Tehran bazaar).
Too many actions in too many places
