No one comes to the fore in those old-fashioned libraries, don't they?
Spijkenisse, a bedroom city located at the doors of Rotterdam that deserves just a fleeting visit, has the doubtful honour of having stood up with a record to forget.
The population of 80,000 has the lowest literacy rate in the Netherlands.
To counter this shameful situation, some years ago it was decided to contribute somehow to the general culture and copy the seven fictional bridges that appear represented in the euro banknotes in the form of decorated reinforced concrete miniatures.
The success of the educational offensive was limited.
And so it was decided by the politicians that there was only one way to improve statistics: there had to be a library!
Winy Maas, from the Dutch architecture studio MVRDV, an entire master in the art of bar diagrams and responsible for fun buildings together as cynical, took the subject with its usual serenity and appeared at the presentation of the competition in 2003 with five books under the arm and a smile on the face.
And as the jury looked perplexed around him and shrugged his shoulders, Maas proceeded to stack the books by size forming a pyramid and concluded his brief speech with the following words: "Dear fellows:
Here you have it, my proposal for the mountain of books by Spijkenisse, the so-called 'Boekenberg'".
Nine years later, the 30 million euro mountain rises in the expected place.
This is part of the revitalization project, which is complemented by underground parking, a supermarket, a post office and a couple of housing buildings and townships.
In early November the mountain of books was awarded the second prize "Best Library of NL 2012".
In addition, the project is also nominated for the "Dutch National Wood Award 2012".
In this way, the little town lacking history, which so far had nothing more to offer than a pedestrian postmodern area and an incredibly ugly city after whose white facade one would rather intrude a milk plant, now has a contemporary architectural work.
But above all, Spijkenisse now has the first public cultural building in its history.
The Long Road to the Book
The first impression is that it is a book paradise under a cheese maker.
It is true that there is an elevator that carries us right to the center of this massive mountain, but the true lovers of space and reading do not use it, but rather they prefer to merge with their topography every step of their climbing to the top.
The fully glazed interior is bright and easy to cover with the view, the recycled brick floor and the elegant lighthouses unequivocally support the public condition of the library.
The urban environment is perfect.
By raising the view you can see the park banks, the dogs and the boys and girls playing football.
And everywhere books, books and more books.
"The bookshelf shelves are usually arranged along the facade and in the centre there is a huge dark room that usually is somewhat uncomfortable and impersonal," says Winy Maas.
What we've done is put our legs up the classic spatial configuration and pull the reading area from the inside out.
The interior of the mountain is very well exploited: the offices, the Internet library, the chess club, the environmental education centre and the maintenance room are located in the middle.
Special mention deserves the black shelves that assume the functions of wall covering, parapet and railing at the same time.
The sight, touch and smell are strange.
Even architects and civil engineers more daily shake their heads when they hear of this unknown material.
"We wanted to work with recycled materials," explains Joop Trouborst, project leader in the city of Spijkenisse.
And that is how one day, on a Frisian farm, we encounter the appropriate by-product from agriculture.
For many years, in the greenhouses and in the fields of the Netherlands a plastic fabric of scarce millimetres of thickness has been used as a basis for holding the roots of crops.
It is cheap and efficient.
This thin fabric lasts two seasons and then is discarded.
For the library this fabric was first taken in such quantities until it obtained plates of four centimeters thick.
With heat and pressure, the so-called agricultural plastic (KLP) changes color and becomes a dark, homogeneous and resistant material that smells like a new car mix and sport slipper.
After 105 footpaths you reach the top of the mountain.
At the end of this continuous route of almost 500 meters around the mountain awaits us the reward: from the café you not only have a fantastic view of the city, but in it you can also enjoy tasty Dutch croquettes and their ficus planted in huge pots.
These create a pleasant atmosphere at the same time that maintains the right atmospheric humidity for this mountain of literature.
Donations to a new soul
"Although it is difficult to believe it given its large crystallized surfaces, this building is an exemplary project with regard to ecology," Trouborst says.
The required heating and cooling are obtained from geothermal energy.
Although the mountain of books is located under a huge pyramid of glass, even in the sunny days the sun only shines for a few hours inside it.
The huge wooden circles across the glass facade serve to provide shade and absorb most of the sun's rays.
This creates a comfortable interior climate.
The rest is automatic blinds.
Stefan Spermon, the skeptical worker in the Information Technology sector, has already dared to set foot in the new library.
And Lisette Verhaig has been there too.
Similarly, traditional Chinese medicine teacher Cynthia Bogarde has visited the library. She calls the "Boekenberg" as Spijkenisse's "late soul".
The reason is that, at the inauguration that took place a couple of weeks ago, all the inhabitants of the city were invited to donate a book from their private collection.
In this way it is intended to fill, at the moment, the optical gaps of a library that does not yet have its complete file; currently it has 70,000 copies.
The concept has gone deep.
The shelves are full.
"There is nothing worse than an empty medium library," says architect Winy Maas.
"I believe that thanks to our initiative now all inhabitants have a certain link with this building.
Everyone knows your book is part of the library.
Even though I'm just there to decorate.
In this way, the MVRDV study has achieved a complete success in this discipline queen that in the specialized argot is known as "creation of an identity".
The city of Spijkenisse has written a piece of the history of literature.
Regardless of how young and uncultivated it may be.
Finally a starting point to shape your identity.
