The prosecutors tried to prove on Friday that Private Bradley Manning, accused of the greatest leak of confidential information in the history of the United States, lost multiple opportunities to report the ill-treatment he now claims he suffered while under military detention.
During the interrogation carried out by the prosecution in a pretrial hearing in Ft. Meade, Maryland, Prosecutor Ashden Fein stated that the records of the weekly visits of officers of the unit that Manning received during nine months of detention in Quantico, Virginia, show no complaints about the treatment he was receiving.
The interrogation, which took place during a hearing carried out following the defence ' s request to dismiss the case as its imprisonment had been harsh and that it had already been sufficiently punished, came one day after Manning had testified that he had planned to commit suicide while he was in detention.
