WikiLeaks has never confirmed that Manning was the source of information.
In view of Friday, Fein reviewed with Manning the forms that officers completed after visits to Manning during his arrest at Quantico military prison, where he was held in maximum detention from July 2010 to April 2011.
Officers would have asked Manning questions and noted his answers.
When on Friday Fein asked about the forms, Manning recognized that he had qualified the treatment given to him by the celators as "excellent" and the treatment received at the facilities in general as "very professional".
The forms show no complaints of ill-treatment, although the officers asked Manning directly about the treatment he was receiving, Fein said.
Manning replied that he had expressed concern about some issues and that the officers visiting him had spoken about these issues and had indicated to him that they would be dealt with, but that they did not record those issues in the register.
"They wrote 'no incident' (after having talked about the problems) but this does not necessarily mean that I had not mentioned any problems," Manning said.
The judge, Army Colonel Denise Lind, also asked Manning why he had not denounced the treatment he received during the meeting that took place in January 2011 with a council to examine the suicide intentions he had expressed in a form months earlier.
Manning replied that his intention during that meeting was to obtain the reduction of the “injury prevention” regime under which he was present.
The military said that they had placed him under that restrictive regime, which was below the level of possible suicide surveillance, in order to guarantee his protection and security for others.
"I wanted the state to know that I was okay and (I wanted) to stop being under injury prevention... in order to enjoy what, from my point of view, is a better quality of life," Manning said.
Manning testified on Thursday about his arrest in Iraq and his transfer to Kuwait, where he was held for nearly two months before being transferred to military prison at the Marine Base in Quantico, Virginia, in July 2010.
He said he had considered suicide in Kuwait and once lost consciousness due to heat.
He said that the fact that he was not allowed to know what was happening to him or what was happening in the outside world was very distressing.
"My world was only reduced to Arafjon Camp, to that cage," Manning explained on Thursday.
"I thought I was going to die in that cage."
Manning said that, once transferred to Quantico, he spent most of the days in a small cell, at least for 21 hours and often for 23 hours, without company.
Manning said he was only allowed to have a mattress, a blanket, some chalks, some clothes and glasses.
He explained that he was trying to move all the time, since it was forbidden to sleep or even fall asleep during the day.
Manning said he always had a light from outside pointing to his eyes while he was asleep.
He said that if the janitors couldn't see his face when he turned around at night, they would wake him up to turn himself around again.
Manning's lawyer filed a formal claim in January 2011 on the treatment Manning received.
Manning was transferred to Fort Leavenworth military prison in Kansas in April 2011.
On Friday the judge asked Manning about an argument he had made in the Thursday statement, according to which, after being forced one night to sleep naked in his Quantico cell, he was forced during a morning count to stand naked in front of the janitors and other prisoners.
Manning had testified that he had never been given the opportunity to cover himself with the blanket during the count.
During the judge's interrogation on Friday, Manning said he deduced from the order that he had given him the coven that he should drop the blanket he could have covered with, but recognized that no one had ordered him to drop it.
Manning testified on Thursday that they had forced him to sleep naked the night before because of an attempt to prove to an officer that he did not pose a danger to himself.
Manning stated that he had told the officer that he could have used the elastic of his underwear or his chalks to self-injury but that he had not.
Manning testified that that night they had removed from their cell their underwear, their chalks and glasses.
His lawyers hope that the judge will at least take into account the experiences he had experienced during his stay in prison and drastically reduce his sentence if he was convicted on the war council, which is expected to start early next year.
The defence stated that it plans to have Manning find himself guilty of minor crimes and to defend other accusations considered too extreme.
The hearing is expected to resume this weekend and prosecutors are expected to argue that the conditions of detention are justified.
The Pentagon has argued that Manning was held in accordance with the rules of application to any detained person who is in maximum custody in Quantico.
The charges against Manning include cooperation with the enemy, unlawfully causing the publication of information on the Internet, leaking information from the national defence and theft of property or public records.
If he is found guilty of all charges, he could face life imprisonment.
