But there are more and more academics and experts in child development who praise the kindness of boredom.
According to them, it is good that we and our children both get bored from time to time.
Boring forces the brain to look for interesting options and may encourage creativity.
Since most of us are currently connected to this or that screen, we do not experience the benefits of boredom.
So, should we accept boredom in good spirits?
Yeah.
And no.
But we'll talk about it later.
First, like many people, it was assumed that, now that we have more time for leisure, boredom would be a relatively recent phenomenon.
But, as Peter Toohey, professor of Greek and Roman History at the University of Calgary, Canada, says, and author of the book "Boredom: A Lively History" ("The Boring, An animated History") published in 2011 by Yale University Press, is not so.
"In fact, the history of boredom is very extensive," he says.
On the walls of Pompeii there are Latin graffiti on the boredom dating from the first century AD.
We must also consider how we define boredom.
"The problem is that it has already been defined and discussed in many ways," says John D. Eastwood, professor of psychology at York University in Ontario, Canada.
After examining the published research and raising the idea before a discussion group of 100 people, Professor Eastwood and his colleagues defined boredom as the experience of "wanting, but unable, to participate in an activity that fills you."
He claims that the difference between boredom and apathy is that the person does not do anything but wants to do it.
He points out that there is no desire to do anything with apathy.
The main experience of boredom, he says, is "the alteration of the care process, associated with a low mood and a feeling that time passes slowly."
Boring may sound awfully like depression.
However, Professor Eastwood says that while they may be related, people who are bored tend to view the problem as a matter of the environment or the world, while people who are depressed consider the problem to have it.
Sometimes we think we're bored, when what really happens to us is that we have trouble concentrating.
In his study "The Uncommitted Mind: Defining Boredom in Terms of Attention", published in the September edition of the journal Perspectives on Psychological Science, Professor Eastwood and his colleagues referred to an earlier experiment in which participants heard a tape of a person reading the article of a magazine.
Some groups heard in the next room a television program at any volume that had no relationship, others heard it with the low volume, so it was barely perceptible, while the third group did not listen to the audio at any time.
The group that listened to the program with the low volume showed more boredom than the other two groups; it cost them to concentrate, but they were not sure why and attributed it to boredom.
"When you try to focus on a difficult or interesting task, the alteration of attention can lead to boredom," said Mark J. Fenske, professor of Neuroscience at Guelph University, Ontario, and one of the authors of the study.
"On the other hand, when you're doing something boring, like detecting defective parts on a manufacturing line, a music that distracts you can help you not to get bored."
"In fact, at present we know that moving or making squirts, actions that are often interpreted as a sign of boredom, can actually help fight it, as it makes that person physically more alert."
"Research shows that those children who are allowed to move learn more and retain more information than those who are forced to be quiet," says Professor Fenske.
We all know what it is like to get bored at some point: the delay of an airplane, a monotonous speaker, a particularly boring film.
But some people tend to get bored more than others.
To help measure it, some researchers developed in the 1980s a "scale of tendency to boredom".
The scale includes issues like "many of the things I have to do are repetitive and monotonous" and "there are so many things that I'm interested in that I don't have time to do everything."
Stephen Vodanovich, professor of psychology at the University of West Florida, says that, using these scales, researchers have discovered that boys tend to get bored more often than girls, and specifically need more external and more varied stimulation.
In general, however, adolescents are a type of group that is quite easily bored.
In 1991, Reed Larson, professor of human and community development at the University of Illinois, conducted an experiment in which he contacted 400 adolescents and his parents seven to eight times a day through a search.
He found that 32 percent of teenagers said he was bored while in school or doing homework, while 23 percent said he was bored when he was not in school.
On the other hand, 3 percent of parents said they were bored.
Professor Larson said he did not know whether the current boredom rates, 21 years later, would be higher or lower.
But he said what he did know was that "adolescence is a period when boredom reaches its highest odds", largely because both children and adolescents are not given great control over what they want to do.
So back to my question at the beginning: Is it good to get bored?
Sometimes it is not, because, led to the extreme, it can make us expose ourselves to absurd physical risks, such as betting or falling into substance consumption as a method of combating it, as shown by research.
On the other hand, many philosophers and writers speak of the connection between boredom and creativity, says Professor Vodanovich, who has been studying this issue for more than two decades.
"The boredom is the way the brain has to tell you that you should be doing something else," says Gary Marcus, professor of psychology at the University of New York.
But the brain doesn't always know what's most appropriate.
If you're bored and use that energy to play the guitar or cook, you'll be satisfied.
But if you see TV, it may satisfy you in the short term, but not in the long run.
"So if your child is bored and you give him an iPad, he may no longer be bored, but he will not have learned to entertain himself or dosify himself," says Professor Fenske.
And "that ability to dose applies to other situations," he says.
Your child not only learns to enjoy himself but also learns to control himself better in other areas.
I don't think we really want to praise boredom.
But neither should we be too critical of him.
Our objective should be, rather, to feel comfortable away from the constant rumor of activities and technologies.
Professor Eastwood agrees.
"In our view, we need to get bored more, but boredom is a desire too distressing and disturbing as to relate it to something worth it," he says.
It points out that what people are really looking for is a way to disconnect and enjoy a dead time.
"In an environment where we are constantly overstimulated," he says, "it is difficult to find ways to focus our attention when the noise stops."
